ğŸ“˜ Today I learned how to find the Minimum and Maximum values in a Binary Search Tree (BST)! ğŸŒ²

After learning different types of traversals and BFS (Level Order), I dove deeper into retrieving the smallest and largest values in a BST, which is super efficient thanks to the treeâ€™s inherent structure.

ğŸ” Key Concept:
The minimum value in a BST lies in the leftmost node.

The maximum value in a BST lies in the rightmost node.

ğŸ”§ Here's the JavaScript code I wrote:
javascript
Copy
Edit
min(root){
    if(!root.left){
        return root.value;
    } else {
        return this.min(root.left);
    }
}

max(root){
    if(!root.right){
        return root.value;
    } else {
        return this.max(root.right);
    }
}
âœ… Example:
For this BST:

markdown
Copy
Edit
        10
       /  \
      5   15
     / \
    3   7
min() returns 3

max() returns 15

â± Time Complexity:
Best/Average Case: O(log n)

Worst Case (skewed tree): O(n)

Loving how clear and logical tree operations become once you understand their structure! On to deletion operations next. ğŸ’»

